nodes.body: awaiting-review

1. `getLeanLibs` was written by Mario and then updated by Kim: I trust that it does what it says!  See [this Zulip thread](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/270676-lean4/topic/Accessing.20.60lean_lib.60s.20in.20a.20lake.20executable).
2. Moving the position in CI of `lake exe mk_all`: I am not sure.  I remember that there were (and still there are) two separate steps of CI that create `Mathlib.lean`.  I may have moved one, since at the time I understood CI even less than I do now.
ðŸš€ Pull request has been placed on the maintainer queue by grunweg.
(At some point, the shell script can also be removed: do you want to do so in this PR? Either way is fine with me.)

I would keep the script a little longer: the shell script does not require having a working version of `lake`.  I am not sure if this is important, but there may be some use for a simple-minded script.
To emphasize the fact that CI will fail if there are files that are not imported, note that the exit code of `lake exe mk_all` is the number of files that were created/modified by the command.

This PR/issue depends on:
* ~~leanprover-community/mathlib4#11853~~

Thanks for doing this! This looks very good to me; I left only minor comments. (Please consider these a sign of appreciation, that I read the code very closely.) Some places are quite clever, I learned a lot!

I did not review the main logic in "getLeanLibs" carefully (looks plausible, though); neither did I check the last ten lines with the command-line set-up. If it works, that's presumably good enough...
Michael, thank you for the comments!  I am trying to add all your suggestions, but Git seems uncooperative: I'll try again!
Thanks for the swift response. I just approved the script itself on the other PR, so only the CI parts remain. A few details are not quite clear to me...

Now this makes sense to me - thanks for following through on this.
maintainer merge

In case you are wondering: the check if all imports are present is removed *as a separate workflow step*, but is part of the build workflow (and runs before getting the cache or building mathlib). So, users still get early feedback, just via a different channel.
Can you rename `stdout` to something more descriptive?

Perhaps
```suggestion
  let ml.lean := addExtension âŸ¨mlâŸ© "lean"  -- for example, `Mathlib.lean`
I renamed it to `allModules`.

```suggestion
      let mlDir := ml.push pathSeparator   -- for example, `Mathlib/`

Can you explain why you added this check? Is this to catch files still indexed by git which have been deleted locally?
If so, adding a comment would be helpful (at least, for my future self).

Added this comment:
```
-- this check is helpful in case the `git` option is on and a local file has been removed
```

```suggestion
/-- `getLeanLibs` returns the names (as an `Array` of `String`s) of all the libraries

```suggestion
   If you are working in a project downstream of mathlib, use `lake exe mk_all --lib MyProject`."

I found the phrasing "the package" confusing, and needed to while to understand what it was about. "the workspace root" is correct, but a mouthful of jargon.
What do you think about  "if the current project is `mathlib`"? This should be understandable to almost all users, and still conveys the essential information.
I like this and I used it!

This entry seems stale.
```suggestion

Why did this move? I presume when this was a tactic, you needed mathlib to be built - is this still the case now? I would think this script could build independently of mathlib.

(Same question for the other three copies.)
To update my question: this didn't move, this got *added* - is this intentional or a merge mishap?

Ok, that's weird.  There should be a CI step that recreates `Mathlib`, `Tactic`, `Counterexamples` and `Archive`: this is used to make sure that they get built and work.

This step was *not* introduced in this PR, but should be already present in regular CI.  This PR should simply shift to using `lake exe mk_all` for this, instead of the bash script.

Besides this, it is true that regular CI builds `Mathlib` once before this step.  I suspect that this is the step that was present before `Archive` and `Counterexamples` were added to be able to cache their oleans.  It is possible that there could be a single step that updates these "import all" files, but I would not investigate this here.
@grunweg is this now considered "resolved" at least as far as this PR is concerned?

Yes, it is: the check if all imports are present (for mathlib, archive, counterexamples and `Mathlib/Tactic`) is removed as a separate workflow step, but is now part of the build workflow (and runs before getting the cache or building mathlib). So, users still get early feedback, just via a different channel.
Just adding this step means this script is executed *twice*: once when checking imports (in line 67 and onwards), and a second time here. Are both of these really necessary?
Also: the job in line 67 still uses the shell script - can it be rewritten in Lean instead?

Ok, yes, you were right all along: the job on line 67 was supposed to be removed by this PR and replaced by the `lake exe mk_all` script.  I probably meant to remove it after testing, but I tested it and then forgot to remove it!  Now I should have removed the shell script from CI.
